The problem involves finding the number of red balls in the second urn. Let \( r \) be the number of red balls in the second urn. The first urn has 8 red and 7 blue balls, totaling 15 balls. The second urn has \( r \) red balls and 9 blue balls, totaling \( r + 9 \) balls.

The probability of drawing two balls of the same color is the sum of the probabilities of both being red or both being blue. This is given as \( \frac{151}{300} \).

The probability both are red is \( \frac{8}{15} \times \frac{r}{r + 9} \).  
The probability both are blue is \( \frac{7}{15} \times \frac{9}{r + 9} \).  
So the equation is:  
\[ \frac{8}{15} \cdot \frac{r}{r + 9} + \frac{7}{15} \cdot \frac{9}{r + 9} = \frac{151}{300} \]

Factor out \( \frac{1}{15} \) and \( \frac{1}{r + 9} \):  
\[ \frac{1}{15} \cdot \frac{1}{r + 9} (8r + 63) = \frac{151}{300} \]

Multiply both sides by 15:  
\[ \frac{8r + 63}{r + 9} = 15 \times \frac{151}{300} = \frac{15 \times 151}{300} = \frac{2265}{300} = \frac{151}{20} \]

So:  
\[ \frac{8r + 63}{r + 9} = \frac{151}{20} \]

Cross-multiply:  
\[ 20(8r + 63) = 151(r + 9) \]  
\[ 160r + 1260 = 151r + 1359 \]  
\[ 160r - 151r = 1359 - 1260 \]  
\[ 9r = 99 \]  
\[ r = 11 \]

