- \( D_0 = 2.4287 \, \text{eV} \)
- \( \omega_e = \nu_e / c = 1405.65 \, \text{cm}^{-1} \)
- \( \omega_e x_e = \nu_e x_e / c = 23.20 \, \text{cm}^{-1} \)

First, compute ZPE in \(\text{cm}^{-1}\):
\[
\text{ZPE} = \frac{1}{2} \times 1405.65 - \frac{1}{4} \times 23.20 = 702.825 - 5.80 = 697.025 \, \text{cm}^{-1}
\]

Convert ZPE to eV using the conversion factor \( 1 \, \text{cm}^{-1} = 1.23984 \times 10^{-4} \, \text{eV} \):
\[
\text{ZPE}_{\text{eV}} = 697.025 \times 1.23984 \times 10^{-4} = 0.086420 \, \text{eV}
\]

Now, calculate \( D_e \):
\[
D_e = D_0 + \text{ZPE}_{\text{eV}} = 2.4287 + 0.086420 = 2.515120 \, \text{eV}
\]

Considering significant figures, \( D_0 = 2.4287 \, \text{eV} \) has five significant figures, and the input parameters limit the precision. The term \( \omega_e x_e = 23.20 \, \text{cm}^{-1} \) has four significant figures, which affects the ZPE calculation. The result \( 2.515120 \, \text{eV} \) is rounded to five significant figures, giving \( 2.5151 \, \text{eV} \).

